  "prompt": "Which guitar should I buy in range of 7 to 8k?",
  "response": "When looking for a guitar in the 7,000 to 8,000 range, there are several options available depending on your preferences (acoustic vs. electric), playing style, and brand loyalty. Here are some recommendations across different categories:\n\n### Acoustic Guitars:\n1. **Yamaha FG830** - A well-balanced acoustic guitar known for its rich tones and good playability.\n2. **Fender CD-60S** - Offers great sound and build quality, perfect for beginners and intermediate players.\n3. **Takamine GD20** - A solid wood guitar that provides excellent sound projection and warmth.\n\n### Electric Guitars:\n1. **Squier Classic Vibe Series** - Great value for money, these guitars offer vintage vibes and excellent playability.\n2. **Epiphone Les Paul Standard** - A more affordable alternative to Gibson guitars, with solid construction and great tone.\n3. **Ibanez RG Series** - Known for their fast necks and versatile sound, suitable for rock and metal genres.\n\n### Semi-Hollow or Hollow Body:\n1. **Epiphone Dot** - Offers a classic semi-hollow design with a warm sound that\u2019s versatile for various genres.\n2. **Gretsch G2622** - Known for its unique sound and aesthetics, great for rockabilly or jazz.\n\n### Considerations:\n- **Playability**: Make sure to try the guitar to see how it feels in your hands.\n- **Sound**: Each guitar has a unique sound profile, so it's a good idea to test different options.\n- **Style**: Choose based on the genre of music you prefer to play.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- Consider buying used to get a higher-end model within your budget.\n- Don't forget to factor in extras like a case, picks, and an amplifier (for electric guitars).\n- If possible, visit a music store to try out different models and get a feel for what resonates with you.\n\nRemember to trust your own ears and hands when selecting a guitar!",
